WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.120
You get in a lot of these, like there's like language wars

00:00:02.120 --> 00:00:04.480
and oh, we used to use this and now we use this,

00:00:04.480 --> 00:00:05.720
or this is so much better than that.

00:00:05.720 --> 00:00:08.440
Any programming language that's popular

00:00:08.440 --> 00:00:10.200
has like a really good reason for being.

00:00:10.200 --> 00:00:12.840
It's funny, I was listening to another interview

00:00:12.840 --> 00:00:16.680
with John Carmack, who did all the Doom and Quake

00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:17.920
and all the id stuff,

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:19.639
and more recently worked on the Oculus.

00:00:19.639 --> 00:00:23.680
And he's legendary for getting every single ounce

00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:25.719
out of the hardware, doing crazy stuff

00:00:25.719 --> 00:00:29.920
with like video buffers and assembly and total maniac.

00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:31.120
And the interview, he was like,

00:00:31.120 --> 00:00:32.680
I kind of need to like realize

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:34.560
that sometimes like Python is great.

00:00:34.560 --> 00:00:37.200
There's a lot of cases where it just doesn't matter.

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:38.480
You know, the best programming language

00:00:38.480 --> 00:00:41.320
is the one that works generally that you're currently using.

00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:44.599
I'm very agnostic in how I think about all these tools.

00:00:44.599 --> 00:00:47.720
I think any tool that gets adoption, I have respect for.

00:00:47.720 --> 00:00:49.000
And I'm kind of curious, like,

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:50.840
well, why is this getting adopted?

00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:53.360
And why do people use this and care about it?

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:01.759
This episode of Ken's Nearest Neighbors

00:01:01.759 --> 00:01:04.599
is powered by Z by HP, HP's high compute,

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:07.400
workstation grade line of products and solutions.

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:10.160
Today, I had the pleasure of interviewing JJ Allaire.

00:01:10.160 --> 00:01:12.879
JJ is the founder of RStudio

00:01:12.879 --> 00:01:15.519
and the creator of the RStudio IDE.

00:01:15.519 --> 00:01:17.320
He's an author of several packages

00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:19.760
in the R Markdown publishing ecosystem,

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:24.760
including R Markdown, Flex Dashboard, LearnR, and Distil.

00:01:24.879 --> 00:01:28.000
And he also worked extensively on the R interfaces

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.239
to Python, Spark, and TensorFlow.

00:01:30.239 --> 00:01:32.400
JJ is now leading the Quarto project,

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:34.559
which is a new Jupyter-based scientific

00:01:34.559 --> 00:01:36.199
and technical publishing system,

00:01:36.199 --> 00:01:38.400
which I'll be doing a project on shortly.

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:40.720
In this episode, we learn about why RStudio

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:43.239
has now repositioned itself as Posit,

00:01:43.239 --> 00:01:46.480
how it maximizes its open-source nature as a B Corp,

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:49.080
and how JJ, as an open-source advocate,

00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:51.440
views the private nature of many LLMs.

00:01:51.440 --> 00:01:52.680
I really enjoyed this conversation,

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:54.080
and I hope you will as well.

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:55.639
JJ, thank you so much

00:01:55.639 --> 00:01:57.760
for coming on the Ken's Nearest Neighbors podcast.

00:01:58.519 --> 00:02:00.480
You bet, happy to be here.

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:02.279
Yeah, you've done such awesome stuff

00:02:02.279 --> 00:02:03.720
in the open-source communities,

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:05.720
and obviously working with R,

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:07.360
and now transitioning into Posit.

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:11.440
I'm so excited to hear what your journey's been like,

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:13.240
and also maybe a little bit about

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:15.960
what the future of open-source,

00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:20.960
as well as the continuation of a lot of technical concepts

00:02:22.399 --> 00:02:24.279
through the platforms you're building.

00:02:24.279 --> 00:02:25.800
You got it, yeah.

00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:27.160
First of all, welcome.

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:31.119
Second, I'm interested in how you first

00:02:31.119 --> 00:02:32.320
got interested in data.

00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:34.880
It might have been a series of careers ago,

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:37.279
but to me, that is one of the kernel questions.

00:02:37.279 --> 00:02:39.440
Absolutely, it was a long time ago, actually.

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:44.440
I was 13 years old, and I was a huge baseball fan.

00:02:46.119 --> 00:02:48.720
Like a lot of 13-year-olds,

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:50.520
I watched a ton of baseball on TV,

00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:52.800
read all about it in magazines,

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:57.279
and I got exposed to a writer named Bill James,

00:02:57.279 --> 00:02:59.800
who many listeners have probably heard of,

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:01.720
but not necessarily everybody.

00:03:01.720 --> 00:03:03.160
So he wrote this series of books

00:03:03.160 --> 00:03:05.399
called the Bill James Baseball Abstract,

00:03:05.399 --> 00:03:07.520
where he used data analysis

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:10.240
to understand the game a lot better.

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:12.039
And one of the things he did was

00:03:12.039 --> 00:03:15.720
he actually exposed the fact

00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:18.440
that a lot of the conventional wisdom about baseball,

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:20.800
how players were valued,

00:03:20.839 --> 00:03:24.759
how games are won and lost, was actually wrong.

00:03:24.759 --> 00:03:28.520
And a lot of the reasoning that went on

00:03:28.520 --> 00:03:31.479
was just basically based on people's intuitions

00:03:31.479 --> 00:03:34.199
and subjective experience, but not based on data.

00:03:34.199 --> 00:03:36.240
And that was just a huge,

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:38.559
and it turned out Bill James,

00:03:38.559 --> 00:03:40.320
when he started, was a heretic.

00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:45.320
He had a 28-page hand Xeroxed newsletter.

00:03:45.479 --> 00:03:48.320
It turned out he ultimately revolutionized all of baseball.

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:50.039
If people have seen the movie Moneyball,

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:52.160
it's based on Bill James' work.

00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:56.639
And now sabermetrics is an entire discipline,

00:03:56.639 --> 00:03:58.679
and all the sports now are very quantitative.

00:03:58.679 --> 00:04:01.160
And that was really in large part due to Bill James.

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:02.759
Anyway, he got me to see,

00:04:02.759 --> 00:04:07.479
wow, if all these experts

00:04:07.479 --> 00:04:09.759
running around saying these things that are not true

00:04:09.759 --> 00:04:12.520
and are so easily debunked by using data,

00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:14.160
that that's a really fundamental thing

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:17.799
that is clearly probably going on outside of sports.

00:04:17.799 --> 00:04:21.839
And my real sort of main interest

00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:25.600
was political science and politics and economics.

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:27.480
And I went to study that in college.

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:28.959
And I was very attracted

00:04:28.959 --> 00:04:31.399
to the empirical research side of that

00:04:31.399 --> 00:04:32.440
because it was the same thing.

00:04:32.440 --> 00:04:33.480
Wow, we're making these really

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:36.239
consequential public policy decisions.

00:04:36.239 --> 00:04:39.200
Are we informing those decisions based on data?

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:41.399
And so in college, I really focused a lot on quantitative

00:04:41.399 --> 00:04:43.119
analysis, I ended up using a bunch of tools

00:04:43.119 --> 00:04:46.359
that some of which are still in wide use today,

00:04:46.679 --> 00:04:51.679
like Excel and tools like SAS and Stata and Jump and SPSS.

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:53.519
And I was really fascinated by it.

00:04:53.519 --> 00:04:54.880
I really enjoyed that work.

00:04:56.359 --> 00:04:58.600
And that took a detour in my career

00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:00.440
where I kind of got into computing.

00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:03.320
And I spent 10 or 15 years building other types

00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:05.480
sort of development tools, programming tools,

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:09.480
web servers, authoring tools, et cetera.

00:05:09.480 --> 00:05:11.000
And when I kind of got done with all that,

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.760
I really was very keen on working in open source software.

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:19.200
And I found out about, I heard about R,

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:21.640
which was an open source statistical computing system.

00:05:21.640 --> 00:05:24.160
And that was very, very compelling to me.

00:05:24.160 --> 00:05:26.160
Because that was sort of where my heart started

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:28.040
in my professional life was like,

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:31.119
how can we use data to understand the world better

00:05:31.119 --> 00:05:33.440
and make better decisions?

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:37.119
And R at the time was early.

00:05:37.119 --> 00:05:40.920
And it was designed by statisticians.

00:05:40.920 --> 00:05:42.920
So it's extremely well suited to its purpose,

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:45.600
but it also needed a lot of tooling.

00:05:46.440 --> 00:05:50.279
And so I started working on open source tooling for R.

00:05:50.279 --> 00:05:51.160
So that's kind of how I got into this.

00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:53.480
So I love that.

00:05:53.480 --> 00:05:56.480
Obviously, I have a massive connection

00:05:56.480 --> 00:05:57.600
to the Bill James story.

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:00.079
I mean, my work is in sports analytics.

00:06:00.079 --> 00:06:03.799
And the seminal person in golf is Mark Brody.

00:06:03.799 --> 00:06:06.640
I got to meet him a couple of times last year.

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:08.799
And the way that we view that game

00:06:08.799 --> 00:06:10.519
has completely transformed more recently

00:06:10.519 --> 00:06:12.279
than with Bill James, right?

00:06:12.279 --> 00:06:15.399
I mean, for those that don't know,

00:06:16.239 --> 00:06:19.359
one of the cool things about sports analytics

00:06:19.359 --> 00:06:22.160
is everyone looks for a singular metric

00:06:22.160 --> 00:06:25.160
that you can evaluate everyone against apples to apples.

00:06:25.160 --> 00:06:27.279
And in baseball, that was wins above replacement.

00:06:27.279 --> 00:06:28.679
In golf, that's strokes gained.

00:06:28.679 --> 00:06:32.760
And it completely changes how these sports are viewed.

00:06:34.679 --> 00:06:35.519
But-

00:06:35.519 --> 00:06:37.720
I want to share an anecdote about that.

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:39.720
Just remind me when we get on to talking

00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:40.880
about some of the other stuff,

00:06:40.880 --> 00:06:44.959
about literate programming and notebooks and things,

00:06:45.799 --> 00:06:47.679
I've got a Bill James-related tie-in

00:06:47.679 --> 00:06:50.079
based on an interview he did very recently

00:06:50.079 --> 00:06:50.920
that I want to share.

00:06:50.920 --> 00:06:53.760
So just make a note of that.

00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:55.519
Okay, I made a note of that.

00:06:55.519 --> 00:06:58.440
So we're going to get into all of that,

00:06:58.440 --> 00:06:59.519
which I'm very excited about.

00:06:59.519 --> 00:07:01.880
But before that, I'm interested in what particularly

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:03.679
drew you to open source.

00:07:03.679 --> 00:07:06.880
You know, that's something that obviously

00:07:06.880 --> 00:07:08.399
has been a massive benefit to my career.

00:07:08.399 --> 00:07:11.920
I think every data scientist out there

00:07:11.959 --> 00:07:12.839
that's worth their brain assault

00:07:12.839 --> 00:07:15.279
is using open source tools.

00:07:15.279 --> 00:07:20.119
And it's really cool for me to see how involved

00:07:20.119 --> 00:07:22.440
and how much you grow in open source communities

00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:23.279
in your own.

00:07:23.279 --> 00:07:24.359
Can you just tell me about like,

00:07:24.359 --> 00:07:26.200
what was the kernel that drew you?

00:07:26.200 --> 00:07:29.959
Well, part of it is I think in science in particular,

00:07:31.079 --> 00:07:34.799
it's very important that people are able to share

00:07:34.799 --> 00:07:36.839
and reproduce results with each other

00:07:36.839 --> 00:07:39.040
and innovate on methods.

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:41.440
And I think that open source does those things

00:07:41.959 --> 00:07:42.799
very, very well.

00:07:42.799 --> 00:07:45.880
If I do some analysis and I want you to evaluate it,

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:48.399
you don't need to purchase a software.

00:07:48.399 --> 00:07:51.200
If I want to reproduce the analysis in 10 years,

00:07:51.200 --> 00:07:52.920
I don't need to make sure I still have a license

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:54.959
or make sure the software still runs.

00:07:54.959 --> 00:07:58.839
If a group of people like in the sports analytics community

00:07:58.839 --> 00:08:02.959
wants to do a bunch of innovation on methods,

00:08:02.959 --> 00:08:06.239
then they don't have to lobby a proprietary software vendor

00:08:06.239 --> 00:08:08.959
and say, oh, hey, pay attention to sports analytics,

00:08:08.959 --> 00:08:10.040
it's really important.

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:11.480
Could you support this,

00:08:11.480 --> 00:08:14.000
the following new cutting edge methods?

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:17.359
So a lot of things, I think,

00:08:17.359 --> 00:08:19.440
specifically about science and inquiry

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:22.079
and trying to develop pools of knowledge in communities

00:08:22.079 --> 00:08:25.119
are really, really well served by open source.

00:08:25.119 --> 00:08:26.399
So I think that's one of the reasons

00:08:26.399 --> 00:08:28.920
why it's really important in data science and science.

00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:30.760
But for me personally,

00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:33.359
I also like the idea of making contributions

00:08:33.359 --> 00:08:34.520
that are durable,

00:08:34.520 --> 00:08:37.760
contributions that can be around in several decades

00:08:37.760 --> 00:08:41.719
that aren't sort of tied to the fate of a given

00:08:41.719 --> 00:08:45.799
or the fate or the whims of like a single company.

00:08:45.799 --> 00:08:47.640
And so that's very attractive.

00:08:47.640 --> 00:08:51.320
I think a reason that I wanted to work in open source

00:08:51.320 --> 00:08:53.200
is these durable contributions.

00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:54.320
But it turns out, I think,

00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:55.520
for data science and science,

00:08:55.520 --> 00:08:57.400
it's a pretty fundamental requirement.

00:08:58.679 --> 00:09:00.000
Yeah, something you've mentioned

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:01.159
in some of the talks you've given

00:09:01.159 --> 00:09:04.799
is that your goal isn't just to be around this year

00:09:04.799 --> 00:09:05.640
or next year,

00:09:05.679 --> 00:09:07.679
it's to be able to produce something

00:09:07.679 --> 00:09:09.760
that's still working in a hundred years.

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:10.599
Yeah, that's right.

00:09:10.599 --> 00:09:13.760
I think that philosophically,

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:15.359
that's so dramatically different

00:09:15.359 --> 00:09:16.960
than what you described might happen

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:21.640
in a private organization or maybe in a startup.

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:23.200
Can you talk to me about how,

00:09:24.760 --> 00:09:27.000
in some settings where things are built privately,

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:29.039
they might actually break down

00:09:29.039 --> 00:09:30.960
because of the incentive structure.

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:35.320
If you look at the history of proprietary software,

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:37.640
typically there are like transition points

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:39.880
where software is like phased out,

00:09:39.880 --> 00:09:42.000
formats are discarded.

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:48.000
Customers are forced to migrate from one thing to another.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:49.719
Customers are abused

00:09:49.719 --> 00:09:51.640
because they have a dependency on the software

00:09:51.640 --> 00:09:53.400
and really have no choice but to keep doing it.

00:09:53.400 --> 00:09:56.320
So I think it's really important for,

00:09:56.320 --> 00:09:58.320
again, this concept of durability

00:09:58.320 --> 00:09:59.919
and this concept of trust

00:09:59.919 --> 00:10:02.039
that we're trying to create something

00:10:02.039 --> 00:10:05.239
that you can rely on for a very long time.

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:11.159
That hundred-year idea is this is trustworthy and durable.

00:10:11.159 --> 00:10:13.159
But it's also, I think, the idea that

00:10:13.159 --> 00:10:18.159
if we can create a company that has a synergistic relationship

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:20.520
between sort of building a business

00:10:20.520 --> 00:10:22.440
and being able to invest at scale

00:10:22.440 --> 00:10:25.000
and creating open-source software,

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.359
that company is worth having around for a hundred years.

00:10:28.359 --> 00:10:30.760
Traditionally, software companies don't work that way.

00:10:30.760 --> 00:10:32.679
There are definitely examples

00:10:32.679 --> 00:10:34.919
of open-source software companies.

00:10:35.080 --> 00:10:39.239
But even like the classic example that people point to

00:10:39.239 --> 00:10:41.239
is like the paragon of successful

00:10:41.239 --> 00:10:43.599
open-source software companies like Red Hat.

00:10:43.599 --> 00:10:45.799
And I just saw a news item yesterday

00:10:45.799 --> 00:10:49.400
where Red Hat's gonna make it much, much harder

00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:52.880
for sort of non-Red Hat distributions

00:10:56.039 --> 00:10:58.280
like Oracle Linux or Amazon Linux,

00:10:58.280 --> 00:11:00.359
or there's various flavors that are derived from Red Hat.

00:11:00.359 --> 00:11:01.400
They're gonna make that much harder.

00:11:01.400 --> 00:11:06.400
So it's, you know, the ability to do something

00:11:06.679 --> 00:11:08.280
that people can trust for the long-term,

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:11.039
I think, is the big driver behind that.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.080
So how can you create a system for that,

00:11:15.080 --> 00:11:17.479
for example, at Posit to be able to do that

00:11:17.479 --> 00:11:18.320
for the long-term?

00:11:18.320 --> 00:11:20.960
I mean, go ahead.

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:23.320
No, no, I think that we talk about it

00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:26.159
as sort of a virtuous cycle where, you know,

00:11:26.159 --> 00:11:28.080
our mission is to create open-source software

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:31.440
that's usable by anyone regardless of economic means,

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:35.599
that's extremely useful to a whole broad range of people.

00:11:35.599 --> 00:11:38.440
And so we do that, you know, that's our packages,

00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:42.159
our IDEs, our web frameworks, reporting tools,

00:11:42.159 --> 00:11:44.359
all the different things we create.

00:11:44.359 --> 00:11:47.760
And by making them open-source,

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:50.799
they tend to get very widely adopted.

00:11:50.799 --> 00:11:54.640
And what happens is that people in large enterprises

00:11:54.640 --> 00:11:57.719
adopt them and then want to do more with them.

00:11:58.359 --> 00:11:59.760
They basically want to, like, integrate them

00:11:59.760 --> 00:12:01.440
with their authentication systems,

00:12:01.440 --> 00:12:03.919
integrate them with their compute grids,

00:12:03.919 --> 00:12:06.239
and, you know, integrate them with their sort of,

00:12:06.239 --> 00:12:08.200
like, audit requirements.

00:12:08.200 --> 00:12:09.840
And there's lots of things that come up

00:12:09.840 --> 00:12:12.239
in a larger setting when you're scaling.

00:12:12.239 --> 00:12:14.599
And our idea is, what we've done,

00:12:14.599 --> 00:12:18.119
is we've sold products to larger enterprises

00:12:18.119 --> 00:12:21.440
who are starting to take these platforms seriously.

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:23.640
And that builds a business for us,

00:12:23.640 --> 00:12:26.559
and that internalizes us to reinvest in open-source

00:12:26.760 --> 00:12:28.880
and ultimately create more opportunities

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:31.080
for other folks to adopt the tools.

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:33.400
So that has worked pretty well for us.

00:12:34.280 --> 00:12:35.400
I'd like to take a quick second

