00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:46.320
I wanted to talk about this a little later,

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:47.479
but since we're on topic,

00:13:47.479 --> 00:13:50.039
I think it, I want to touch on it now.

00:13:50.159 --> 00:13:55.000
What is, I notice that a Posit is a B Corp.

00:13:56.919 --> 00:13:59.000
Can you explain a little bit what that means,

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:00.960
but also how that sort of ties into what we're talking about?

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:04.760
Yeah, a B Corp is a benefit corporation,

00:14:04.760 --> 00:14:08.239
and in short, in very short,

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:13.479
the nature of corporations in the United States

00:14:13.479 --> 00:14:15.080
is that they're really,

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:18.159
their exclusive ultimate responsibility

00:14:18.159 --> 00:14:19.679
is to their shareholders.

00:14:20.479 --> 00:14:23.000
So they have a fairly narrow definition

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:25.679
of what's ultimately important,

00:14:25.679 --> 00:14:28.760
and that can lead to companies, again, as I said,

00:14:28.760 --> 00:14:31.719
selling themselves, becoming abusive,

00:14:33.559 --> 00:14:35.679
and that's problematic

00:14:35.679 --> 00:14:38.840
because companies really have a bunch of stakeholders.

00:14:38.840 --> 00:14:40.440
They have their customers,

00:14:40.440 --> 00:14:43.359
the broader community, their employees,

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:46.200
and what a benefit corp is

00:14:46.200 --> 00:14:48.359
is it sort of broadens the idea

00:14:48.359 --> 00:14:49.599
of what a corporation is for,

00:14:50.159 --> 00:14:51.440
and it broadens the accountability

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:54.960
to say it's accountable to multiple groups of stakeholders.

00:14:54.960 --> 00:14:57.799
Further, public benefit corporations

00:14:57.799 --> 00:15:01.159
define a public benefit, a specific mission,

00:15:01.159 --> 00:15:03.000
that they're also obliged to pursue.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.359
In our case, it's open source software for science.

00:15:05.359 --> 00:15:07.200
So it's a new type of company

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:11.559
that has been developed really in the last 10 or 15 years,

00:15:11.559 --> 00:15:14.119
and we made the transition.

00:15:14.119 --> 00:15:16.440
It actually didn't exist in a robust form

00:15:16.440 --> 00:15:19.280
when we started our studio,

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:22.479
but we made the transition, I think, a few years ago,

00:15:22.479 --> 00:15:25.359
three or four years ago, to being a benefit corp,

00:15:25.359 --> 00:15:29.400
partly because we wanted to have it in,

00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:32.239
that idea of durability and who we're accountable to,

00:15:32.239 --> 00:15:33.919
we wanted to be in our charter,

00:15:33.919 --> 00:15:35.239
and we wanted people to understand

00:15:35.239 --> 00:15:38.200
that we were trustworthy and we meant what we said.

00:15:41.440 --> 00:15:44.000
Meaning what you say, I think, is so important,

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.520
and it also ties in very interestingly

00:15:47.520 --> 00:15:52.520
to, I think, technology communities, particularly engineers,

00:15:52.760 --> 00:15:56.119
because the philosophy of open source

00:15:56.119 --> 00:15:59.119
has always been interesting.

00:15:59.119 --> 00:16:03.119
How do you make that work when there's these individual,

00:16:05.679 --> 00:16:09.119
individual capitalistic mottos of each individual person?

00:16:09.119 --> 00:16:12.479
And I think software engineers feel so much like,

00:16:12.479 --> 00:16:13.640
hey, this isn't how I want it,

00:16:13.640 --> 00:16:14.559
why don't I just do it myself?

00:16:14.559 --> 00:16:16.359
Screw it, I'm gonna build it.

00:16:16.359 --> 00:16:18.039
And you feed into that,

00:16:18.039 --> 00:16:19.919
but you also feed into the ownership

00:16:19.919 --> 00:16:21.679
and the community aspect.

00:16:21.679 --> 00:16:23.719
And psychologically, to me,

00:16:23.719 --> 00:16:27.119
there's very few case studies like that

00:16:27.119 --> 00:16:30.239
where people will actually willingly work together,

00:16:30.239 --> 00:16:32.559
they build something largely for free.

00:16:32.559 --> 00:16:34.039
Yeah, it's amazing.

00:16:34.039 --> 00:16:36.280
Yeah, there's been writing about,

00:16:36.280 --> 00:16:39.239
there's a little bit of a gift economy dimension

00:16:39.239 --> 00:16:44.239
where I think we are fairly advanced industrial civilization

00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:46.559
that's fairly affluent,

00:16:46.559 --> 00:16:50.840
and so people start to turn to other considerations

00:16:50.840 --> 00:16:53.479
like what can I give, what can I contribute,

00:16:53.479 --> 00:16:54.960
how is my work used?

00:16:54.960 --> 00:16:58.400
We're sort of above the providing basic food and shelter.

00:16:58.400 --> 00:16:59.320
And I think what you're saying,

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:02.440
a lot of data scientists and engineers

00:17:02.440 --> 00:17:04.479
that I interact with kind of feel that way.

00:17:04.479 --> 00:17:06.520
They actually do want to create something bigger,

00:17:06.520 --> 00:17:07.359
bigger than themselves,

00:17:07.359 --> 00:17:10.359
and make a contribution to other people in their field.

00:17:11.319 --> 00:17:14.040
Yeah, I mean, realistically,

00:17:14.040 --> 00:17:17.920
I see that making a meaningful contribution to the field,

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:19.319
for a lot of people I've talked to,

00:17:19.319 --> 00:17:21.079
it means a lot more than, for example, money does.

00:17:21.079 --> 00:17:21.920
It does, it does.

00:17:21.920 --> 00:17:22.760
Just being able to say,

00:17:22.760 --> 00:17:25.520
hey, look what I've enabled these other people to build.

00:17:25.520 --> 00:17:27.560
That absolutely does, yeah.

00:17:27.560 --> 00:17:28.760
Yeah.

00:17:28.760 --> 00:17:29.599
Especially I mean for-

00:17:29.599 --> 00:17:31.199
I view, go ahead.

00:17:31.199 --> 00:17:33.160
No, you go ahead, go ahead, sorry.

00:17:33.160 --> 00:17:34.760
I was gonna say, I view a lot of the,

00:17:34.760 --> 00:17:36.119
for example, the content that I create

00:17:36.119 --> 00:17:37.160
in very much the same way,

00:17:37.520 --> 00:17:42.199
where I'm probably not gonna come up with the most,

00:17:42.199 --> 00:17:46.520
anything that inherently creates a tremendous value

00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:48.839
for humanity over the course of my career.

00:17:48.839 --> 00:17:49.800
I might be selling myself short,

00:17:49.800 --> 00:17:51.719
but I feel like that's pretty realistic.

00:17:51.719 --> 00:17:55.319
I mean, I think letting people,

00:17:55.319 --> 00:17:56.839
having conversations with all the people

00:17:56.839 --> 00:17:58.160
you have conversations with,

00:17:58.160 --> 00:18:00.880
opens up a lot of kind of intellectual pathways

00:18:00.880 --> 00:18:02.400
for a lot of people, so.

00:18:02.400 --> 00:18:03.560
Well, that's what it is,

00:18:03.560 --> 00:18:06.319
is if I can inspire someone

00:18:06.319 --> 00:18:07.760
that actually does make that difference,

00:18:07.760 --> 00:18:09.319
to be more interested in the field,

00:18:09.319 --> 00:18:12.439
if one of my videos helps them get started,

00:18:12.439 --> 00:18:14.359
to me that is just as valuable.

00:18:14.359 --> 00:18:15.199
Absolutely.

00:18:15.199 --> 00:18:16.040
And it's in my own way, right?

00:18:16.040 --> 00:18:18.280
Absolutely, yeah, yeah.

00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:21.040
So let's go back a little bit more

00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:22.680
to your specific story.

00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:23.520
Yeah.

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:25.479
You obviously fell in love with open source.

00:18:25.479 --> 00:18:27.000
You started building in this.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.599
How did you get involved with RStudio?

00:18:29.599 --> 00:18:31.920
How did you get to the part

00:18:31.920 --> 00:18:35.359
where you're leading Posit now?

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:37.839
Yeah, so RStudio started,

00:18:37.839 --> 00:18:40.680
I think it was like 12 or 13 years ago.

00:18:40.680 --> 00:18:43.239
And originally it wasn't started to design,

00:18:43.239 --> 00:18:44.439
intended to be a company.

00:18:44.439 --> 00:18:47.680
It was just, hey, let's make an IDE for R.

00:18:47.680 --> 00:18:49.359
You know, I had done programming tools.

00:18:49.359 --> 00:18:50.319
I'd done some IDEs.

00:18:50.319 --> 00:18:51.959
I'd done writing tools.

00:18:51.959 --> 00:18:54.880
And so I said, I think R could really benefit

00:18:54.880 --> 00:18:56.599
from having a nice IDE.

00:18:56.599 --> 00:18:59.000
And so I actually ended up working on that

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:02.040
with Joe Chang, who was the co-founder.

00:19:02.040 --> 00:19:04.280
He's the CTO now.

00:19:04.280 --> 00:19:05.479
So we worked on RStudio.

00:19:05.479 --> 00:19:08.400
We worked on that for a couple, three years.

00:19:08.400 --> 00:19:09.400
We released it.

00:19:09.400 --> 00:19:11.640
It kind of started to get momentum.

00:19:11.640 --> 00:19:14.719
We ended up meeting Hadley Wickham,

00:19:14.719 --> 00:19:16.680
who sort of became another co-founder,

00:19:16.680 --> 00:19:18.319
who's now our chief scientist.

00:19:18.319 --> 00:19:21.560
He had been working on, you know, ggplot and dplyr

00:19:21.560 --> 00:19:24.160
and a bunch of really, really popular R packages

00:19:24.160 --> 00:19:26.400
for doing data analysis and visualization.

00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:28.839
And so we said, hey, let's all work together.

00:19:28.839 --> 00:19:31.439
Let's all see what happens if we all work together.

00:19:31.439 --> 00:19:32.719
And that was sort of the birth

00:19:32.719 --> 00:19:35.160
of it being more than just a single project,

00:19:35.160 --> 00:19:38.119
because by that time we had four or five people

00:19:38.119 --> 00:19:40.599
and we kind of had to decide, you know,

00:19:40.599 --> 00:19:42.959
are we going to try to make this a small company?

00:19:42.959 --> 00:19:44.319
Are we going to try to grow it?

00:19:44.319 --> 00:19:47.400
And we decided that there were a lot of other folks

00:19:47.400 --> 00:19:49.119
we knew who could make contributions

00:19:49.119 --> 00:19:52.560
and it would be really valuable to try to grow the company.

00:19:53.479 --> 00:19:57.880
And so, and then we teamed up with Tarif Kowaf,

00:19:57.880 --> 00:19:59.680
who's someone who's now our president.

00:19:59.680 --> 00:20:01.959
So he's been here for also for over 10 years.

00:20:01.959 --> 00:20:04.560
And he kind of came on with the responsibility

00:20:04.560 --> 00:20:06.760
of figuring out, you know,

00:20:06.760 --> 00:20:08.280
how could we create this virtuous cycle?

00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:10.280
How could we create and grow a company

00:20:10.280 --> 00:20:12.079
that supports open source?

00:20:12.079 --> 00:20:13.920
So that was the genesis of RStudio.

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:17.959
And Joe actually came up with a product called Shiny,

00:20:17.959 --> 00:20:20.959
an open source web development server,

00:20:20.959 --> 00:20:24.880
web development framework called, for R,

00:20:24.880 --> 00:20:27.280
for sort of data-centric apps called Shiny.

00:20:27.280 --> 00:20:30.079
And so, you know, we had RStudio, we had Shiny,

00:20:30.079 --> 00:20:32.199
and then we started working on,

00:20:32.199 --> 00:20:35.000
that's okay, let's see if we can create some

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:36.760
sort of enhanced commercial version

00:20:36.760 --> 00:20:37.959
of these things to sell.

00:20:37.959 --> 00:20:39.560
And that ended up working out.

00:20:39.560 --> 00:20:41.839
And so we get the company grew slowly at first,

00:20:41.839 --> 00:20:44.319
you know, to 15 and then 20 and 30 and 50.

00:20:44.319 --> 00:20:46.760
And, you know, we ended up,

00:20:46.760 --> 00:20:48.959
it ended up working really well.

00:20:48.959 --> 00:20:52.439
And we kind of ended up, I would say about three years ago,

00:20:54.319 --> 00:20:56.599
we had sold our products to lots of customers,

00:20:56.599 --> 00:20:59.880
but we observed that every data science team

00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:02.280
that we were selling into was doing,

00:21:02.280 --> 00:21:05.199
we started off with like these sort of very R-centric groups

00:21:05.199 --> 00:21:08.719
but basically everybody was using R and Python.

00:21:08.719 --> 00:21:11.959
Or, you know, maybe there'd be some exclusively R

00:21:11.959 --> 00:21:14.119
and some exclusively Python groups,

00:21:14.119 --> 00:21:17.560
but the vast majority of groups were using both.

00:21:17.560 --> 00:21:20.000
And we were selling, you know, enterprise software

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.880
to help those teams be productive and deploy things.

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:24.880
And so it was like sort of not,

00:21:24.880 --> 00:21:27.520
it didn't make sense to sell them an R-only thing.

00:21:27.520 --> 00:21:28.880
It just didn't compute at all.

00:21:28.880 --> 00:21:32.880
So we started, we added support for Python

00:21:32.880 --> 00:21:35.199
to sort of all of our products.

00:21:36.479 --> 00:21:37.520
And that was well-received,

00:21:37.520 --> 00:21:39.719
but it's quite difficult for customers

00:21:39.719 --> 00:21:43.239
to get their head around buying like Python solutions

00:21:43.239 --> 00:21:45.239
from a company called RStudio.

00:21:45.239 --> 00:21:47.439
It was like, just really like,

00:21:47.439 --> 00:21:49.800
wow, how am I going to explain this to the CIO?

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:51.319
Like we're buying, you know.

00:21:51.319 --> 00:21:54.560
And so we decided a couple of years ago

00:21:54.560 --> 00:21:56.560
that we really need to change the name of the company

00:21:56.560 --> 00:22:00.079
so that people understand the kind of the bigger breadth

00:22:00.079 --> 00:22:01.400
of what we're doing.

00:22:01.400 --> 00:22:03.239
And also at the same time,

00:22:03.239 --> 00:22:06.040
kind of change some of the focus of our open source work

00:22:06.040 --> 00:22:09.599
where we had really been really primarily aimed

00:22:09.599 --> 00:22:13.560
at doing open source in the R ecosystem.

00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:16.400
And we decided that when we do new projects,

00:22:16.400 --> 00:22:18.479
we need to make them multi-language.

00:22:18.479 --> 00:22:22.280
And so we ended up doing Shiny for Python.

00:22:22.280 --> 00:22:24.839
That was announced like a year ago.

00:22:24.839 --> 00:22:26.800
Quarto, which is a project that I'm working on,

00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:29.040
was Python from the beginning.

00:22:29.040 --> 00:22:33.119
So we're essentially trying to evolve the company

00:22:33.119 --> 00:22:35.680
to one that creates open source data science software

00:22:35.680 --> 00:22:37.280
for both Python and R,

00:22:37.280 --> 00:22:39.800
sells commercial products for both Python and R.

00:22:39.800 --> 00:22:42.119
And so we renamed the company Posit.

00:22:42.119 --> 00:22:45.119
That's about a year ago to reflect that.

00:22:47.119 --> 00:22:49.079
You know, renaming the company,

00:22:49.079 --> 00:22:53.239
I think that that is so in line with the open source nature.

00:22:53.359 --> 00:22:55.719
You know, it's, hey, we're a community,

00:22:55.719 --> 00:22:56.680
we're trying to build things

00:22:56.680 --> 00:22:58.760
that are most valuable to people,

00:22:58.760 --> 00:23:00.640
and we're gonna take this in the direction

00:23:00.640 --> 00:23:03.359
that the group is seeing this,

00:23:03.359 --> 00:23:06.040
or like that the users are seeing this.

00:23:06.040 --> 00:23:10.280
And I feel like that's something that most companies

00:23:10.280 --> 00:23:14.199
in a more like traditional profit-motivated

00:23:15.880 --> 00:23:20.199
like zone or would really struggle to do,

00:23:20.199 --> 00:23:21.880
because it's like, oh, this is our identity,

00:23:21.880 --> 00:23:22.719
how do we change?

00:23:23.199 --> 00:23:24.439
It's hard because I mean,

00:23:24.439 --> 00:23:27.079
our studio had a really terrific brand,

00:23:27.079 --> 00:23:29.119
had a really good reputation.

00:23:29.119 --> 00:23:31.640
And the easiest thing to do is just keep turning that crank

00:23:31.640 --> 00:23:33.040
and see what happens.

00:23:33.040 --> 00:23:33.880
And I just felt like,

00:23:33.880 --> 00:23:35.920
I actually felt like bigger picture,

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:38.719
like going back, we'd become a benefit corp.

00:23:38.719 --> 00:23:41.599
We'd set up this sort of capital structure

00:23:41.599 --> 00:23:45.280
and group of people capable of delivering

00:23:45.280 --> 00:23:47.199
a much broader set of things.

00:23:47.199 --> 00:23:48.599
And I wanted to go for that.

00:23:48.599 --> 00:23:50.280
You know, even if it was,

00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:52.119
it's obviously quite inconvenient

00:23:52.160 --> 00:23:53.359
to change the name of the company.

00:23:53.359 --> 00:23:54.640
Now, all of a sudden you've gone from,

00:23:54.640 --> 00:23:55.560
everyone's heard of you.

00:23:55.560 --> 00:23:58.239
Even most Python users have heard of RStudio.

00:23:58.239 --> 00:23:59.319
No one's heard of Posit.

00:23:59.319 --> 00:24:03.479
You know, that's kind of a hard reset,

00:24:03.479 --> 00:24:04.439
but I think it's worth it.

00:24:04.439 --> 00:24:05.959
You know, it'll take time,

00:24:05.959 --> 00:24:08.400
but eventually we're hopeful

00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:09.400
that folks will have heard of us.

00:24:09.400 --> 00:24:11.239
It'll be really, really have been

00:24:11.239 --> 00:24:12.680
a very worthwhile transition.

00:24:14.119 --> 00:24:16.040
Let's talk a little bit about

00:24:16.040 --> 00:24:20.439
maybe where R is most valuable

00:24:20.479 --> 00:24:22.119
or who the R users are

00:24:22.119 --> 00:24:24.000
and how that fits into the broader community.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:26.719
Because to me, that's something,

00:24:26.719 --> 00:24:28.479
you know, for example, in sports,

00:24:28.479 --> 00:24:31.040
R, especially with the, I think it's the NFL,

00:24:31.040 --> 00:24:33.000
R is the prominent language that they're using.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:34.319
Maybe it's changing a little bit,

00:24:34.319 --> 00:24:36.520
but there's specific communities

00:24:36.520 --> 00:24:39.839
that seem like R is their first choice.

00:24:39.839 --> 00:24:44.439
And some of them are begrudgingly adopting other tools.

00:24:44.439 --> 00:24:46.920
But, you know, why is it so prominent

00:24:46.920 --> 00:24:49.239
in some areas and then some other areas are just like.

00:24:49.239 --> 00:24:50.400
I mean, some of it is,

00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:53.040
I would say that R plays very well.

00:24:53.040 --> 00:24:55.719
Certainly, if you look at like people

00:24:55.719 --> 00:24:58.359
who are like in an undergraduate or graduate setting,

00:24:58.359 --> 00:25:00.439
if you're studying software engineering,

00:25:00.439 --> 00:25:02.280
you are gonna gravitate to Python.

00:25:02.280 --> 00:25:04.119
If you learned about machine learning

00:25:04.119 --> 00:25:05.520
in your computer science department,

00:25:05.520 --> 00:25:08.160
you're absolutely using Python.

00:25:09.520 --> 00:25:12.560
If you are in a company and you're doing data engineering,

00:25:12.560 --> 00:25:14.119
you're using Python.

00:25:14.119 --> 00:25:17.560
If you are in a statistics program,

00:25:17.920 --> 00:25:20.000
an undergraduate or graduate statistics program,

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:22.319
you're very likely using R.

00:25:22.319 --> 00:25:26.439
So there's a lineage of individuals and subfields

00:25:26.439 --> 00:25:29.719
where if you're coming from a heavy statistics orientation,

00:25:29.719 --> 00:25:31.319
you're likely using R.

00:25:31.319 --> 00:25:32.839
And conversely, if you're coming more

00:25:32.839 --> 00:25:36.439
from a computer science data pipeline,

00:25:36.439 --> 00:25:38.000
data engineering, you're using Python.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:41.520
So that's one explanation of where that comes from.

00:25:41.520 --> 00:25:44.400
The other thing though is that many people

00:25:44.400 --> 00:25:49.400
who do work with data do not principally identify

00:25:49.800 --> 00:25:52.199
as a software engineer or software developer.

00:25:52.199 --> 00:25:56.040
They identify as like, I'm a biologist, I'm an economist,

00:25:56.040 --> 00:25:57.760
I'm a sports analytics person.

00:25:57.760 --> 00:26:00.319
And so a lot of them, it gets driven by like,

00:26:00.319 --> 00:26:02.959
what's the package ecosystem look like

00:26:02.959 --> 00:26:05.839
for doing the work that I care about?

00:26:05.839 --> 00:26:07.319
And so you will see subfields.

00:26:07.319 --> 00:26:10.000
My guess is in the NFL, some of it's historical,

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:13.599
but there's probably packages that are extremely useful

00:26:13.599 --> 00:26:16.000
and would be really annoying to do without.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:17.719
And that makes it more sticky there.

00:26:17.719 --> 00:26:22.400
I mean, you can conversely see in deep learning in Python,

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:25.760
like all the places, all the ways in which you wanna do

00:26:25.760 --> 00:26:28.680
deep learning and all the libraries are all in Python.

00:26:28.680 --> 00:26:32.920
So you're just in Python if you're doing neural nets.

00:26:32.920 --> 00:26:35.079
And so I think there's some of that that goes by field.

00:26:35.079 --> 00:26:40.079
We see a huge preponderance of R in insurance,

00:26:40.079 --> 00:26:43.400
and in pharma, those are places that are like,

00:26:43.400 --> 00:26:47.479
actuarial work or research in a clinical setting

00:26:47.479 --> 00:26:49.719
is like very statistics intensive.

00:26:49.719 --> 00:26:51.319
And so you see it more in those settings.

00:26:51.319 --> 00:26:54.319
So I think part has to do with educational background,

00:26:54.319 --> 00:26:58.180
part has to do with package ecosystem,

00:26:59.400 --> 00:27:01.239
how much statistics is a big part of things

00:27:01.239 --> 00:27:02.520
versus machine learning.

00:27:02.520 --> 00:27:04.160
So those are some of the factors.

00:27:05.040 --> 00:27:10.040
I have to think in terms of factors,

00:27:10.040 --> 00:27:12.760
open source actually plays a really large role

00:27:12.760 --> 00:27:13.599
in the communities.

00:27:13.599 --> 00:27:16.280
I mean, just as you said, with the NFL,

00:27:16.280 --> 00:27:19.760
I think NFL scrape R was one of the best ways

00:27:19.760 --> 00:27:21.160
to get NFL data.

00:27:21.160 --> 00:27:25.199
And so if everyone's scraping their data using R,

00:27:25.199 --> 00:27:27.239
then probably will analyze it using R too.

00:27:27.239 --> 00:27:28.079
That's right.

00:27:28.079 --> 00:27:29.160
Exactly.

00:27:29.160 --> 00:27:32.280
And to me, that's such a cool way that open source

00:27:32.280 --> 00:27:35.760
can drive adoption, unity, those things.

00:27:35.760 --> 00:27:37.599
Well, that's what I was talking about the long term.

00:27:37.599 --> 00:27:39.959
There's no way, like Stata was not gonna come up

00:27:39.959 --> 00:27:41.760
with like an NFL scraping feature.

00:27:41.760 --> 00:27:44.079
They just wouldn't have done it.

00:27:44.079 --> 00:27:45.000
Whereas the community says,

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:47.160
hey, we care about this, we wanna do this.

00:27:47.160 --> 00:27:49.079
So here's NFL scrape R.

00:27:51.719 --> 00:27:54.800
Yeah, well, there's other things like that

00:27:54.800 --> 00:27:59.800
where you have these communities

00:28:00.040 --> 00:28:04.319
that are pushing towards sort of this more,

00:28:07.119 --> 00:28:08.560
more specific use cases.

00:28:08.560 --> 00:28:11.319
And I think one we talked about previously was PCA.

00:28:11.319 --> 00:28:12.160
Yeah.

00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:14.239
Like principal component analysis in R

00:28:14.239 --> 00:28:16.400
in the libraries that are available there,

00:28:16.400 --> 00:28:19.719
I find to be so much more effective than the ones in Python.

00:28:19.719 --> 00:28:21.160
It's just more interpretable.

00:28:22.439 --> 00:28:25.400
And if the brunt of your work is doing PCA,

00:28:25.400 --> 00:28:26.239
maybe in a recent-

00:28:26.239 --> 00:28:27.560
Yeah, you're gonna end up in R.

00:28:27.560 --> 00:28:28.400
Public Result.

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:29.239
That's right.

00:28:29.359 --> 00:28:30.719
So that's what we see.

00:28:30.719 --> 00:28:32.119
Yeah.

00:28:32.119 --> 00:28:32.959
Amazing.

00:28:32.959 --> 00:28:34.560
Well, one thing I think is really cool,

00:28:34.560 --> 00:28:37.000
and we talked a little bit about this offline,

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:39.800
is that I see the world becoming more

00:28:39.800 --> 00:28:42.239
and more programming language agnostic.

00:28:42.239 --> 00:28:46.199
So with the expansion of LLMs,

00:28:46.199 --> 00:28:48.880
I now can just take my Python code and say,

00:28:48.880 --> 00:28:51.239
hey, turn this into usable R code.

00:28:51.239 --> 00:28:52.920
Or I could say what I want and say,

00:28:52.920 --> 00:28:56.760
hey, give it to me in JavaScript or Julia or Mojo

00:28:56.760 --> 00:28:58.800
when it's more widely accessible.

00:29:00.239 --> 00:29:05.079
You know, I think that there's a huge democratization

00:29:05.079 --> 00:29:06.079
of programming languages,

00:29:06.079 --> 00:29:09.599
and it's gonna be more about the tooling

00:29:09.599 --> 00:29:12.160
or the libraries or the accessibility

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:15.319
that we can get across any of these platforms.

00:29:15.319 --> 00:29:16.800
Do you have any kind of broader thoughts on that?

00:29:16.800 --> 00:29:20.680
Yeah, I mean, I definitely agree that using LLMs

00:29:20.680 --> 00:29:23.040
lets you bootstrap into a new language

00:29:23.040 --> 00:29:26.479
in a way that's really pretty revolutionary, you know?

00:29:26.479 --> 00:29:27.319
Because a lot of,

00:29:27.439 --> 00:29:29.640
you would normally spend two or three days

00:29:29.640 --> 00:29:31.359
like fumbling around trying to figure out

00:29:31.359 --> 00:29:33.680
which way is up with a new language.

00:29:33.680 --> 00:29:36.000
But you know, you can say, hey, I wanna do whatever,

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:37.520
you know, I'm gonna do a PC analysis,

00:29:37.520 --> 00:29:38.599
I wanna visualize it this way,

00:29:38.599 --> 00:29:42.439
and it'll give you roughly what you need to do,

00:29:42.439 --> 00:29:44.280
and then you're gonna probably have to tweak it

00:29:44.280 --> 00:29:46.000
and fix some problems and whatnot.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:48.239
But I think in terms of accessibility

00:29:48.239 --> 00:29:50.640
of different programming ecosystems,

00:29:50.640 --> 00:29:52.640
it is pretty profound.

00:29:52.640 --> 00:29:56.000
You know, I think, I will say that I do think that

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:00.479
there's a lot of like skill that's developed

00:30:00.479 --> 00:30:03.199
by data scientists or programmers

00:30:03.199 --> 00:30:05.640
ends up being fairly deep knowledge

00:30:05.640 --> 00:30:07.640
of the language and language ecosystem

00:30:07.640 --> 00:30:09.680
and vagaries of it and workarounds.

00:30:09.680 --> 00:30:11.359
And so I think, you know,

00:30:11.359 --> 00:30:14.160
the investment people make in a given language

00:30:14.160 --> 00:30:15.959
is still pretty sticky.

00:30:15.959 --> 00:30:17.439
You know, I don't know that people are gonna be like

00:30:17.439 --> 00:30:19.640
just flitting around between languages

00:30:19.640 --> 00:30:23.319
because you are giving up a lot when you switch languages.

00:30:24.239 --> 00:30:27.119
So yeah, we'll see how that,

00:30:27.119 --> 00:30:30.479
I definitely feel like people are really feel empowered

00:30:30.479 --> 00:30:32.920
to try things that they don't understand that well

00:30:32.920 --> 00:30:34.839
because they can get going really quickly

00:30:34.839 --> 00:30:36.959
with LMs for sure.

00:30:36.959 --> 00:30:39.599
Maybe it'll be more like, you know,

00:30:39.599 --> 00:30:42.880
people who maybe currently use SPSS or Excel

00:30:42.880 --> 00:30:46.040
or something that's a little less code oriented

00:30:46.040 --> 00:30:47.800
will feel more empowered to say,

00:30:47.800 --> 00:30:49.760
hey, wow, I got started, I created a notebook

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:51.959
that does kind of like what I was doing in Excel,

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:54.880
it all works and it's really flexible

00:30:54.880 --> 00:30:56.680
and now I'm off and running.

00:30:58.239 --> 00:31:00.880
Yeah, I think the sort of cold start problem

00:31:00.880 --> 00:31:02.719
is very difficult for a lot of people.

00:31:02.719 --> 00:31:06.359
It's, you know, hey, I know that this

00:31:06.359 --> 00:31:08.839
would probably look better and be more adaptable

00:31:08.839 --> 00:31:10.719
if I was using JavaScript,

00:31:10.719 --> 00:31:13.439
but I've written five lines of JavaScript code

00:31:13.439 --> 00:31:14.479
in my entire life.

00:31:14.479 --> 00:31:15.319
Yeah, yeah.

00:31:15.319 --> 00:31:16.760
All five of those being Hello World.

00:31:16.760 --> 00:31:20.719
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:31:20.719 --> 00:31:24.439
And to me, it's like, well, the barrier to entry

00:31:24.439 --> 00:31:27.479
to be able to be competent in that,

00:31:27.479 --> 00:31:29.959
but then to expand that knowledge

00:31:29.959 --> 00:31:34.000
is so much lower than it used to be in the past.

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:37.439
And I think I'm super interested in where that goes.

00:31:37.439 --> 00:31:41.959
I also think in particular, coding tools

00:31:41.959 --> 00:31:45.119
being accessible to people who are doing research

00:31:45.119 --> 00:31:47.000
is really interesting.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:48.839
It is, it is.

00:31:48.839 --> 00:31:52.119
You know, you were talking about political science.

00:31:52.119 --> 00:31:54.239
Political science research is now enabled

00:31:54.239 --> 00:31:57.319
by the ability to code more effectively,

00:31:57.319 --> 00:32:00.959
to apply more quantitative rigor,

00:32:00.959 --> 00:32:04.479
because, you know, Python isn't as much of a barrier,

00:32:04.479 --> 00:32:05.959
R isn't as much of a barrier,

00:32:05.959 --> 00:32:08.880
any of these tools aren't as much of a barrier.

00:32:08.880 --> 00:32:11.719
You know, you're really focused also on research

00:32:11.719 --> 00:32:13.439
and publishing with Quarto.

00:32:13.439 --> 00:32:14.719
Tell me a little bit more about that.

00:32:14.719 --> 00:32:18.040
Yeah, so actually, the open source project

00:32:18.040 --> 00:32:20.400
that I've been working on for the last few years,

00:32:20.400 --> 00:32:22.280
it's called Quarto.

00:32:22.280 --> 00:32:24.920
And really, it's a platform,

00:32:24.920 --> 00:32:26.959
or platform's probably the wrong word.

00:32:26.959 --> 00:32:31.959
It's a framework for publishing reports and research

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:34.959
that have data at their center.

00:32:34.959 --> 00:32:38.959
So it's for creating reproducible documents.

00:32:38.959 --> 00:32:41.800
It's for creating artifacts from data analysis

00:32:41.800 --> 00:32:43.599
that go beyond just like a single metric,

00:32:43.599 --> 00:32:46.040
but, you know, a suite of data visualizations,

00:32:46.040 --> 00:32:48.479
narrative that accompanies visualizations,

00:32:48.479 --> 00:32:51.040
notebooks that you created that dig into a topic

00:32:51.040 --> 00:32:52.959
and make them available as a website,

00:32:52.959 --> 00:32:55.000
or make them available inside a presentation.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:59.160
So Quarto is really about communicating.

00:32:59.160 --> 00:33:01.000
And I wanted to bring a little bit

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:02.439
of the motivation for this.

00:33:02.439 --> 00:33:04.359
And, you know, it really,

00:33:04.359 --> 00:33:06.319
one of the fundamental capabilities of Quarto

00:33:06.319 --> 00:33:08.439
is that it can take Jupyter notebooks

00:33:08.439 --> 00:33:10.599
and can publish them in a huge variety of formats.

00:33:10.599 --> 00:33:13.760
So you can create entire books or, you know,

00:33:13.760 --> 00:33:18.560
a blog or a presentation, a PowerPoint presentation,

00:33:18.560 --> 00:33:23.199
a Word document, a really attractive searchable website.

00:33:23.199 --> 00:33:24.439
So you can take Jupyter notebooks

00:33:24.439 --> 00:33:26.680
and actually bring them to a lot of people.

00:33:27.520 --> 00:33:28.920
That's one of the fundamental capabilities.

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:30.439
And I think if you go back

00:33:30.439 --> 00:33:32.880
to like what's interesting about Jupyter,

00:33:32.880 --> 00:33:36.040
and we were talking a little bit earlier

00:33:36.040 --> 00:33:38.160
about Bill James and Sabermetrics,

00:33:38.160 --> 00:33:40.959
and there was an interview he did,

00:33:40.959 --> 00:33:44.119
I think about a month ago with Michael Lewis.

00:33:44.119 --> 00:33:49.079
And he said that he, I had not heard him say this,

00:33:49.079 --> 00:33:52.000
but he has become sort of disillusioned

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:54.760
with the contemporary sports analytics movement

00:33:54.760 --> 00:33:56.199
because there's so folk,

00:33:56.199 --> 00:33:57.760
you mentioned that wins above replacement,

00:33:57.760 --> 00:34:00.400
like we need to get one number, you know,

00:34:00.400 --> 00:34:02.479
that represents the player's value.

00:34:02.479 --> 00:34:06.719
And Bill James's work always had context and narrative,

00:34:06.719 --> 00:34:09.360
and, but, you know, consider this.

00:34:09.399 --> 00:34:11.959
And he sort of became, he says become disillusioned

00:34:11.959 --> 00:34:13.439
because it's always just about like getting it,

00:34:13.439 --> 00:34:15.520
reducing to a single number.

00:34:15.520 --> 00:34:17.520
And he said, there's just a lot more going on

00:34:17.520 --> 00:34:20.000
when you're thinking about players and teams

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:21.000
and careers and all that.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:25.360
So I think that what Jupyter notebooks allow you to do

00:34:25.360 --> 00:34:28.080
as a publishing medium, and by extension, Quarto,

00:34:28.080 --> 00:34:31.600
is marry narrative to visualizations,

00:34:31.600 --> 00:34:34.600
to those reductions that you get

00:34:34.600 --> 00:34:36.760
in terms of numbers and things.

00:34:36.760 --> 00:34:41.159
So oftentimes there's just a lot of context assumptions,

00:34:41.159 --> 00:34:44.560
qualifications, other branches to consider

00:34:44.560 --> 00:34:46.479
in a rigorous analysis.

00:34:46.479 --> 00:34:48.760
And part of the focus of Quarto

00:34:48.760 --> 00:34:50.600
is helping you communicate those.

00:34:51.679 --> 00:34:53.199
That's so interesting to me,

00:34:53.199 --> 00:34:56.360
because I see that so much in my own work

00:34:56.360 --> 00:35:00.719
is that every data scientist wants to qualify their work.

00:35:00.719 --> 00:35:03.479
We say this holds true when X, Y, Z.

00:35:03.479 --> 00:35:04.320
Right, right.

00:35:04.320 --> 00:35:06.080
Every business person just wants,

00:35:06.399 --> 00:35:08.239
hey, what is this number to tell us how to work?

00:35:08.239 --> 00:35:09.760
What is this number?

00:35:09.760 --> 00:35:12.280
Yeah, and there's so much storytelling,

00:35:12.280 --> 00:35:13.600
there's so much background in that

00:35:13.600 --> 00:35:17.120
that is very difficult for us to convey

00:35:17.120 --> 00:35:19.679
because data scientists, engineers,

00:35:19.679 --> 00:35:21.719
we tell the story from the beginning.

00:35:21.719 --> 00:35:25.879
And business people, they want the story from end to,

00:35:25.879 --> 00:35:29.000
basically they just want the end or the conclusion.

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:32.080
And that's not, you can't make great decisions

00:35:32.080 --> 00:35:33.360
with just the end.

00:35:33.360 --> 00:35:35.639
You need to understand the context.

00:35:36.040 --> 00:35:38.120
I recommend, listen to that interview if you can.

00:35:38.120 --> 00:35:40.919
It's really fascinating,

00:35:40.919 --> 00:35:43.360
him kind of reflecting on his career

00:35:43.360 --> 00:35:46.120
and kind of where things have gone.

00:35:47.159 --> 00:35:49.399
There's another worthwhile thing to read,

00:35:49.399 --> 00:35:53.439
which was Edward Tufte wrote a pamphlet,

00:35:53.439 --> 00:35:55.760
people are probably familiar with some of his books,

00:35:55.760 --> 00:35:58.719
the visual display of quantitative information,

00:35:58.719 --> 00:36:01.320
called the cognitive,

00:36:01.320 --> 00:36:02.159
it was, I think it's called

00:36:02.159 --> 00:36:03.800
The Cognitive Style of PowerPoint,

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:06.040
called Pitching Out Corrupts Within.

00:36:06.040 --> 00:36:09.679
And he basically describes how trying to reduce

00:36:10.760 --> 00:36:14.560
decisions and analysis to like a single graph,

00:36:14.560 --> 00:36:17.560
a single three bullets, a single number

00:36:17.560 --> 00:36:20.280
leads to oftentimes like terrible consequences.

00:36:20.280 --> 00:36:21.120
That's true.

00:36:21.120 --> 00:36:22.320
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:36:22.320 --> 00:36:23.159
So he actually showed,

00:36:23.159 --> 00:36:24.760
one of his examples was he showed like

00:36:24.760 --> 00:36:27.919
the ill-fated space shuttle mission.

00:36:27.919 --> 00:36:29.120
There's like a PowerPoint deck

00:36:29.120 --> 00:36:31.439
where they basically were talking about,

00:36:31.439 --> 00:36:32.760
should we do this or not?

00:36:32.760 --> 00:36:33.600
And there's some slide,

00:36:33.600 --> 00:36:34.840
it's just got like four bullets

00:36:34.840 --> 00:36:36.719
and there's a bunch of other detail

00:36:36.719 --> 00:36:37.560
that needs to be explored

00:36:37.560 --> 00:36:40.239
and it's just, it ended up on one slide.

00:36:41.199 --> 00:36:42.239
Like a really important thing

00:36:42.239 --> 00:36:43.560
was just sort of meshed over

00:36:43.560 --> 00:36:45.560
and the idea of like let's reduce it down.

00:36:45.560 --> 00:36:46.520
Yeah, and they are, you know,

00:36:46.520 --> 00:36:50.120
the whole, you know, the Wall Street value at risk,

00:36:50.120 --> 00:36:52.560
you know, it's like we have our value at risk metric

00:36:52.560 --> 00:36:55.280
and that's gonna tell us like how exposed we are.

00:36:55.280 --> 00:36:56.879
