00:48:24.260 --> 00:48:27.699
And I know in Sam's testimony,

00:48:27.699 --> 00:48:29.860
he made it clear like we don't think

00:48:29.860 --> 00:48:33.179
this should impact open source and startups.

00:48:33.179 --> 00:48:34.020
He was trying to say,

00:48:34.020 --> 00:48:38.540
we're not trying to do the regulatory capture lock-in thing.

00:48:40.340 --> 00:48:43.300
But some of that is inevitable

00:48:43.300 --> 00:48:44.379
and I think it has to do

00:48:44.379 --> 00:48:46.260
with like how dangerous these models can be.

00:48:46.260 --> 00:48:48.739
Like I think saying like we wanna foster

00:48:48.739 --> 00:48:53.580
maximum innovation, okay,

00:48:53.620 --> 00:48:56.500
but if it's like we want maximum innovation

00:48:56.500 --> 00:48:59.459
in like development of like new bioweapons,

00:48:59.459 --> 00:49:00.300
we wouldn't say that.

00:49:00.300 --> 00:49:01.620
Like let's have maximum innovation.

00:49:01.620 --> 00:49:03.860
Let's have as many people as possible

00:49:03.860 --> 00:49:05.459
getting in there, making bioweapons,

00:49:05.459 --> 00:49:07.739
trying out different types of bioweapons.

00:49:07.739 --> 00:49:09.659
No one would be like, oh yeah, it's gotta be open.

00:49:09.659 --> 00:49:13.540
So I think that's an extreme example,

00:49:13.540 --> 00:49:18.060
but as the capability of these things improves,

00:49:18.060 --> 00:49:19.979
they do become more dangerous.

00:49:19.979 --> 00:49:21.820
And so I don't think it's just an absolute,

00:49:21.860 --> 00:49:23.659
like we wanna have as much innovation as possible.

00:49:23.659 --> 00:49:27.540
We wanna have as many applications as possible.

00:49:27.540 --> 00:49:31.580
So it's like at some point we might say,

00:49:31.580 --> 00:49:32.699
yeah, it's actually kind of good

00:49:32.699 --> 00:49:34.979
that there's like four people who do this.

00:49:34.979 --> 00:49:35.820
We might.

00:49:35.820 --> 00:49:37.899
Yeah, I tend to agree with you.

00:49:37.899 --> 00:49:40.459
I think playing devil's advocate a little bit.

00:49:42.419 --> 00:49:45.340
These large language models inherently are not a weapon.

00:49:45.340 --> 00:49:47.620
You're going in and saying, hey, this is a bio,

00:49:47.620 --> 00:49:51.580
like we know this is a non-biome weapon doing research.

00:49:52.340 --> 00:49:53.820
There's this weird gray area that we operate in

00:49:53.820 --> 00:49:57.979
where I don't think that there are many technologies

00:49:57.979 --> 00:50:00.260
that are as ambiguous, maybe nuclear is,

00:50:00.260 --> 00:50:03.580
where, okay, if we make advances in nuclear,

00:50:03.580 --> 00:50:05.500
we can power things more efficiently,

00:50:05.500 --> 00:50:07.739
but it also has this destructive capability.

00:50:07.739 --> 00:50:09.820
Classic dual use, yeah.

00:50:09.820 --> 00:50:13.300
To me, it's fascinating because there are so few

00:50:13.300 --> 00:50:18.300
dual use technologies like this that have so much-

00:50:18.300 --> 00:50:20.580
Bio is interesting and things like

00:50:20.580 --> 00:50:24.419
gain-of-function research in order to understand better

00:50:24.419 --> 00:50:28.820
how pathogens work also has the downside of-

00:50:28.820 --> 00:50:29.659
The downside of?

00:50:29.659 --> 00:50:32.780
Yeah, so there's a few, but yeah, you're right.

00:50:32.780 --> 00:50:33.620
There's not that many.

00:50:33.620 --> 00:50:35.300
I think you're right that,

00:50:35.300 --> 00:50:38.899
I think the most dangerous thing about LLMs right now

00:50:38.899 --> 00:50:43.179
is their ability to produce disinformation at scale,

00:50:43.179 --> 00:50:48.179
I think, to so disharmonious political

00:50:49.179 --> 00:50:54.179
and cultural dialogue in social media and other places

00:50:55.979 --> 00:51:00.979
is like the worst thing that they can do right now.

00:51:01.939 --> 00:51:04.139
I don't think that none of these other

00:51:04.139 --> 00:51:08.300
kind of like really more physically frightening scenarios

00:51:08.300 --> 00:51:11.060
are in play or already close to in play,

00:51:11.060 --> 00:51:12.699
but we do need to think about it,

00:51:12.699 --> 00:51:14.540
the fact that Sam Altman said,

00:51:14.540 --> 00:51:16.739
we need to make sure they can't self-replicate, right?

00:51:17.060 --> 00:51:21.340
That is looking toward a future where, huh,

00:51:21.340 --> 00:51:23.300
oh, they're gonna self-replicate, what?

00:51:25.419 --> 00:51:26.699
It's interesting.

00:51:26.699 --> 00:51:29.100
This is my personal take.

00:51:29.100 --> 00:51:34.100
I'm interested in a world where we can't trust any news.

00:51:34.419 --> 00:51:36.020
I think it's an inevitability.

00:51:36.020 --> 00:51:38.419
Yeah, I think that's probably right.

00:51:38.419 --> 00:51:42.179
And I don't know if that's necessarily the worst thing

00:51:42.179 --> 00:51:45.659
because right now we're in this weird limbo state

00:51:45.659 --> 00:51:48.899
where the people or the models

00:51:48.899 --> 00:51:51.060
are good enough to trick most of us,

00:51:51.060 --> 00:51:53.340
but on the other hand,

00:51:53.340 --> 00:51:56.100
there's some news that we can vaguely trust still.

00:51:56.100 --> 00:51:58.820
If we live in a world where we can't trust any news,

00:51:58.820 --> 00:52:00.939
that changes our relationship with media.

00:52:00.939 --> 00:52:02.659
It's like maybe we go to specific people,

00:52:02.659 --> 00:52:05.219
maybe we go back to what journalism was.

00:52:05.219 --> 00:52:08.179
I do wonder if it leads to just like everyone just says,

00:52:08.179 --> 00:52:10.979
well, I'm not going online anymore.

00:52:10.979 --> 00:52:12.739
It's just like I'm literally interacting

00:52:12.739 --> 00:52:14.340
with machines all the time

00:52:14.340 --> 00:52:15.820
and I'm getting like deep fakes

00:52:15.820 --> 00:52:17.540
and I'm just like, I'm not,

00:52:17.540 --> 00:52:20.379
like I'm just gonna have like a book club here

00:52:20.379 --> 00:52:23.219
and in our village and just talk to each other.

00:52:23.219 --> 00:52:24.739
I mean, that wouldn't be terrible.

00:52:24.739 --> 00:52:26.419
And you can't trust the book if it was published recently.

00:52:26.419 --> 00:52:28.860
You can't trust the book, yeah, exactly.

00:52:28.860 --> 00:52:30.260
No, I know.

00:52:30.260 --> 00:52:33.500
I think some shared sense of reality

00:52:33.500 --> 00:52:37.020
is a helpful basis for like civic dialogue,

00:52:37.020 --> 00:52:40.219
but we are, I think, gonna be beyond that

00:52:40.219 --> 00:52:42.020
if we aren't already beyond that.

00:52:42.020 --> 00:52:47.020
Yeah, my optimistic hope is that distrust online

00:52:47.260 --> 00:52:51.500
means that communities and in-person things

00:52:51.500 --> 00:52:53.459
have a resurgence in value.

00:52:53.459 --> 00:52:54.300
Yeah.

00:52:54.300 --> 00:52:57.139
Because, you know, you can,

00:52:57.139 --> 00:52:59.899
there's something inherent about being able to like

00:52:59.899 --> 00:53:01.020
reach out and talk to someone.

00:53:01.020 --> 00:53:03.100
Absolutely, yeah, no, I think you may be right.

00:53:03.100 --> 00:53:04.780
That may be where we end up

00:53:04.780 --> 00:53:07.139
and that would not be a bad thing.

00:53:07.139 --> 00:53:08.459
I completely agree.

00:53:08.459 --> 00:53:11.179
So JJ, those are all the questions I had.

00:53:11.179 --> 00:53:12.699
Do you have any final thoughts?

00:53:12.699 --> 00:53:14.179
Anything you, you know,

00:53:14.179 --> 00:53:15.860
any way people can learn more about you?

00:53:15.860 --> 00:53:17.260
Anything along those lines?

00:53:17.260 --> 00:53:18.580
Happy to share those.

00:53:18.580 --> 00:53:21.100
Yeah, I mean, I think you can put the URL

00:53:21.100 --> 00:53:22.179
for the Quarto project.

00:53:22.179 --> 00:53:23.739
I think it's very much worth,

00:53:23.739 --> 00:53:24.860
if you're a data scientist,

00:53:24.860 --> 00:53:27.040
it's absolutely worth checking out.

